posts.name:
Shail Khiyara
Shail Khiyara
posts.content:
𝗜𝘀 𝗔𝗴𝗲𝗻𝘁𝗶𝗰 𝗔𝗜 𝗙𝗮𝗶𝗹𝗶𝗻𝗴?? 
𝗔 𝗚𝗼𝗼𝗱 𝗧𝗵𝗶𝗻𝗴 𝗳𝗼𝗿 𝗔𝘂𝗴𝗺𝗲𝗻𝘁𝗲𝗱 𝗛𝘂𝗺𝗮𝗻𝗶𝘁𝘆

The conversation around Agentic AI feels like the self-driving car debate all over again. 𝗗𝗼 𝘄𝗲 𝘁𝗿𝘂𝘀𝘁 𝗶𝘁 𝗻𝗼𝘄, 𝗼𝗿 𝗱𝗼 𝘄𝗲 𝘄𝗮𝗶𝘁 𝗳𝗼𝗿 𝗽𝗲𝗿𝗳𝗲𝗰𝘁𝗶𝗼𝗻?

This question was raised in a thought-provoking post byand it echoes themes from an insightful article onabout the 𝗹𝗶𝗺𝗶𝘁𝘀 𝗼𝗳 𝗔𝗴𝗲𝗻𝘁𝗶𝗰 𝗔𝗜. Both explore 𝘄𝗵𝗲𝘁𝗵𝗲𝗿 “𝗴𝗼𝗼𝗱 𝗲𝗻𝗼𝘂𝗴𝗵” 𝗶𝘀 𝗿𝗲𝗮𝗹𝗹𝘆 𝗲𝗻𝗼𝘂𝗴𝗵.

Here’s the reality:

 The 𝗮𝘂𝘁𝗼𝗻𝗼𝗺𝗼𝘂𝘀 𝗻𝗮𝘁𝘂𝗿𝗲 𝗼𝗳 𝗮𝗴𝗲𝗻𝘁𝘀 often means higher costs and the risk of compounding errors.
 Without 𝗴𝗿𝗼𝘂𝗻𝗱 𝘁𝗿𝘂𝘁𝗵, agents struggle to align with real-world complexity.
 𝗧𝗿𝗮𝗻𝘀𝗽𝗮𝗿𝗲𝗻𝗰𝘆, 𝗶𝗻𝘁𝗲𝗿𝗽𝗿𝗲𝘁𝗮𝗯𝗶𝗹𝗶𝘁𝘆, 𝗮𝗻𝗱 𝗵𝘂𝗺𝗮𝗻 𝗷𝘂𝗱𝗴𝗺𝗲𝗻𝘁 are non-negotiable in workflows.

But this isn’t a failure—it’s a 𝗰𝗼𝘂𝗿𝘀𝗲 𝗰𝗼𝗿𝗿𝗲𝗰𝘁𝗶𝗼𝗻.

Instead of chasing complex, risky systems, we should focus on what works:

1️⃣ 𝗕𝗮𝘀𝗶𝗰 𝗮𝘂𝘁𝗼𝗺𝗮𝘁𝗶𝗼𝗻 𝘀𝘂𝗰𝗰𝗲𝗲𝗱𝘀 where complex chains fail.
2️⃣ 𝗖𝗹𝗲𝗮𝗻 𝗱𝗮𝘁𝗮 𝗯𝗲𝗮𝘁𝘀 𝗯𝗶𝗴 𝗱𝗮𝘁𝗮—dirty data ruins even the best models.
3️⃣ 𝗦𝗶𝗺𝗽𝗹𝗲 𝘀𝗼𝗹𝘂𝘁𝗶𝗼𝗻𝘀 𝘄𝗶𝗻—over-engineering adds cost and compounds errors.
4️⃣ 𝗠𝗲𝗮𝘀𝘂𝗿𝗲 𝗿𝗲𝗮𝗹 𝗿𝗲𝘀𝘂𝗹𝘁𝘀—prioritize outcomes over hype.

The future of AI isn’t about replacing humans. It’s about 𝗮𝘂𝗴𝗺𝗲𝗻𝘁𝗶𝗻𝗴 𝗵𝘂𝗺𝗮𝗻𝗶𝘁𝘆:

️ Start with 𝗰𝗼𝗺𝗽𝗼𝘀𝗮𝗯𝗹𝗲 𝗽𝗮𝘁𝘁𝗲𝗿𝗻𝘀.
️ Build trust with 𝗲𝘅𝗽𝗹𝗮𝗶𝗻𝗮𝗯𝗶𝗹𝗶𝘁𝘆 𝗮𝗻𝗱 𝘁𝗿𝗮𝗻𝘀𝗽𝗮𝗿𝗲𝗻𝗰𝘆.
️ Use AI to 𝗮𝗺𝗽𝗹𝗶𝗳𝘆 𝗵𝘂𝗺𝗮𝗻 𝗱𝗲𝗰𝗶𝘀𝗶𝗼𝗻-𝗺𝗮𝗸𝗶𝗻𝗴, not replace it.

Agentic AI reminds us: 𝗴𝗼𝗼𝗱 𝗲𝗻𝗼𝘂𝗴𝗵 𝗶𝘀𝗻’𝘁 𝗴𝗼𝗼𝗱 𝗮𝘁 𝗮𝗹𝗹 𝗶𝗳 𝗶𝘁 𝗱𝗼𝗲𝘀𝗻’𝘁 𝗱𝗲𝗹𝗶𝘃𝗲𝗿 𝗿𝗲𝗮𝗹 𝘃𝗮𝗹𝘂𝗲. The question isn’t just “deploy now or wait?” It’s 𝗵𝗼𝘄 𝗱𝗼 𝘄𝗲 𝗲𝗻𝘀𝘂𝗿𝗲 𝗔𝗜 𝗮𝗺𝗽𝗹𝗶𝗳𝗶𝗲𝘀 𝘂𝘀, 𝗻𝗼𝘁 𝗿𝗲𝗽𝗹𝗮𝗰𝗲𝘀 𝘂𝘀?

Would love to hear your thoughts—how are you seeing these themes play out in your industry?

posts.content:
Are you lonely at work?

You're not alone.

Studies shows 82% of employees feel isolated at work — that’s almost everyone.

Most people get wrong think "networking" is just for external relationships.

But internal networks matter more than ever.

In my experience, companies with strong internal networks see better outcomes in employee wellbeing.

So why don’t we do it more?

The problem is most people say "I'll connect with colleagues when I have time."

Sadly, that time never comes.

Instead of waiting for inspiration to network internally:

• Block off 2-3 hours each week just for internal relationship building
• Schedule it early in the day (not after you're drained from meetings)
• Make it a protected habit, like any other important work task

Think beyond your direct team:

• Connect with project managers (they touch every part of the company)
• Reach out to people in different departments
• Build bridges between teams you work with

It can be as simple as:

• Looking at your company org chart
• Picking someone you don't know well
• Sending a short "I noticed your work on [project]. Would love to learn more about what you do.”

The best workplace relationships don't happen by accident.

They happen by design.

posts.content:
Young professionals, I know you’ve been told that success takes time

but what if I told you that your ability to embrace change could accelerate your growth?

Let me take you back to when I first started my career. I was so excited about what was to come, eager to prove myself. But then, something unexpected happened.

THE MARKET CHANGED.

And by “changed,” I mean everything I thought I knew about my industry, my role and even my strategy… shifted
(picture this, everything was going in a particular direction and the next thing we saw was the complete opposite; a complete drastic change )

The plan I had worked on for months? No longer relevant. The skills I had just mastered? Now outdated. The strategies I had perfected? Suddenly ineffective.

I was lost. My first instinct was to resist (if you were in my shoes, I'm sure you'd do the same thing ). I wanted to stick to the plan, stay in my comfort zone. But the more I tried to hold on, the more frustrated I became.

That’s when I learned my biggest lesson about success:

️Change is the only constant.
If you're going to grow, you need to embrace change. Don’t fight it. When things shift whether it’s a market trend, a new skill set, or a new role; take it as an opportunity to level up, learn and ADAPT.

️Change can push you beyond your limits. The beauty of change is that it forces you to get uncomfortable. In that discomfort, you find new solutions, develop new skills, and discover new strengths. I realized that stepping out of my comfort zone was the best way to expand it.

️Flexibility is your power.
In this fast-paced world, the ability to pivot is more valuable than having a rigid plan. Whether you’re in marketing, project management, or any field, how quickly you adapt is what will set you apart.

It wasn’t easy but once I learned to roll with the punches and adapt to change, everything started to fall into place.

To every young professional out there:
Embrace change. Change can be as small as leveraging social, updating your linkedin headline, revamping your resume 

What’s a change you’ve had to embrace in your career so far?

Audra Carpenter
posts.content:
Many of you have been asking what’s the big deal with scheduling tasks in ChatGPT.

OpenAI’s recent update introduces a basic but promising feature: scheduled tasks.

It’s currently in early beta, available on certain plans, and comes with a few limitations (like a cap on the number of tasks and token usage).

So why does it matter?

This is likely the first step toward seamless AI agents built right into our workflows.

By simplifying automations, we’re moving closer to a future where our everyday tasks—news briefings, content reminders, and even productivity nudges—are handled directly in the system without the need for additional tools.

It’s just the beginning, but the implications are huge. I’m excited to see where this goes.

posts.content:
𝗪𝗵𝗮𝘁 𝗸𝗶𝗻𝗱 𝗼𝗳 𝗹𝗲𝗮𝗱𝗲𝗿 𝗱𝗼 𝘆𝗼𝘂 𝗮𝘀𝗽𝗶𝗿𝗲 𝘁𝗼 𝗯𝗲?

Leadership challenges like team disengagement, slow progress, or lackluster results can often feel overwhelming.

You might find yourself wondering why your efforts aren’t yielding the impact you want.

Here’s the hard truth:
sometimes it’s not about doing more—it’s about leading differently.

Avoiding tough decisions, clinging to outdated habits, or failing to adapt can create confusion and frustration for your team.

But refining your leadership style can change everything.

These 5 leadership archetypes offer a fresh perspective to help you evolve:
 The Hero: Face challenges head-on and lead by example.

 The Mentor: Empower your team by offering guidance and support.

 The Shadow: Leaders embracing the Shadow archetype confront their inner fears, biases, and vulnerabilities head-on.

 The Explorer: Stay curious and encourage innovation.

 The Ruler: Excels at creating structure, setting clear goals, and ensuring accountability within their teams.

Which archetype will you embrace? Comment below.

️ Found this helpful? Repost to share with your network.
 Followfor actionable advice on leadership, startups, and career growth.
